recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. First spring male. Bird was moving around the lower branches of understory trees in the forest. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

Lunenburg (near  Auburndale), Lunenburg County, Nova Scotia
recordings.rmk:
This recording was originally posted as a mystery recording. With the help of Paul Driver it was identified as a fledgling Magnolia Warbler. 

This species is a breeding bird at this site, and though my view was limited, the yellow belly also pointed to this i.d.

(Original notes: 
Morning, warm, in a field growing up in birch and pine, at edge of mixed deciduous/hemlock forest. Bird was a warbler and had a yellow belly which seemed to extend to the tail--though I am not certain on this. It looked to have a dark undertail, and back was gray, which may or may not include the head--the bird was screened by branches which made it difficult to really get a good look or a photo. The call was a note repeated three times in quick succession. You can hear it in response to my pishing. There are also sounds of chickens in background, and of a squirrel.)
